Scrolling Through Influence: An Instagram Ad Diary

Dewmi Jayatilake

Introduction

Across two separate logging periods, I recorded a total of 40 Instagram ads that appeared on my personal feed — 20 ads from an earlier project, and another 20 collected recently for this one. I tracked what kind of product was being advertised, the format it showed up in (like Story, Video, Image), whether I recognised the brand, how appealing I thought it was, and whether I interacted with it (clicked, liked, saved, etc.).

This story is based entirely on my own scrolling patterns. It reflects what I see on Instagram, when I see it, and what’s most likely to get me to stop and engage. The patterns turned out to be surprisingly clear — here’s what stood out.

What Gets Advertised the Most?

Bar chart showing top 5 product types advertised. Fashion leads, followed by Food & Beverage, Entertainment, Tech/Gadgets, and Beauty/Health.

Fashion dominates my ad feed. That’s not a surprise considering the influencers and clothing brands I follow. Ads for food, entertainment, and gadgets followed — areas that also align with my recent searches and scroll patterns.

These results reflect how Instagram’s algorithms customize content based on users’ digital footprints.

Do Ad Formats Affect Interaction?

Grouped bar chart showing higher interaction rates with Stories and Videos compared to other formats.

From my observations, I was more likely to interact with Stories and Videos than with Images or Reels. These dynamic formats are designed to grab attention and often appear natively between friend updates, making them feel less intrusive.

The structure and timing of the ad — not just the product — clearly influence engagement.

When Do Ads Appear the Most?

Bar chart showing number of ads seen by time of day, with Afternoon being the highest.

Most ads appeared in the afternoon, followed by evening. This matches my personal usage — I scroll the most after university lectures and while taking breaks.

This reinforces how platforms strategically deliver ads when users are most active and responsive.

Summary

Even though this data was logged across two different time periods — one set of 20 ads from a past project and another 20 from the last week — the patterns are consistent:

  • Fashion dominated the types of products being advertised to me.
  • Stories and Videos were more likely to get my attention than static formats.
  • Afternoons were peak ad times, matching when I’m most likely to scroll.

Even with a small and personal data set like this, it’s easy to see how Instagram’s advertising system is designed to match not just who I am — but when and how I interact with content. Once you notice it, it’s kind of hard to ignore.
